<div id="review_3449196525" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3449196525" />
    <a title="Ipsa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56673559-ipsa"><img alt="Ipsa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1640596342p2/56673559.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3449196525?book_show_action=true">Jul 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ipsa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ipsa" href="/user/show/56673559-ipsa">Ipsa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3449196525" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1149726410255750068">Kahlil Gibran is kind of a hit or miss writer, his impact on an individual depends on how privy and inclined they are to his spiritual hyperboles. While I really liked The Prophet, this one was unbelievably mediocre. <br/><br/>A tragic love story commingled with contemplations on love, life and grief, while sounds alluring, fell flat on its face, leaving me absolutely cold to the ultra dramatic trials and tribulations of Selma and Gibran; although there were some passages, certain tid-bits here and there </span>
  <span id="freeText1149726410255750068" style="display:none">Kahlil Gibran is kind of a hit or miss writer, his impact on an individual depends on how privy and inclined they are to his spiritual hyperboles. While I really liked The Prophet, this one was unbelievably mediocre. <br /><br />A tragic love story commingled with contemplations on love, life and grief, while sounds alluring, fell flat on its face, leaving me absolutely cold to the ultra dramatic trials and tribulations of Selma and Gibran; although there were some passages, certain tid-bits here and there worth munching over. <br />But ultimately, his overuse of bejewelled metaphors, exaggerated, and ostentatious dialogues rendered whatever little positive impact the book could've had, absolutely nil.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1149726410255750068" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


